{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17634322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17634322"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:11:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:11:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17512"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17512"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71071"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10202"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17512"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56542"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10063"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23879"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71071"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe citric acid cycle (Krebs cycle) is a central metabolic pathway that occurs in the mitochondrial matrix of cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the products generated from one complete turn of the citric acid cycle using one molecule of acetyl-CoA?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1 CO2, 3 NADH, 1 FADH2, and 2 ATP","3 CO2, 2 NADH, 1 FADH2, and 1 ATP","2 CO2, 3 NADH, 1 FADH2, and 1 GTP","1 CO2, 2 NADH, 2 FADH2, and 2 ATP","2 CO2, 2 NADH, 2 FADH2, and 2 GTP"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor one molecule of acetyl-CoA entering the citric acid cycle, the products are \u003Cstrong\u003E2 CO2, 3 NADH, 1 FADH2, and 1 GTP\u003C/strong\u003E. Here\u0027s how each product is generated:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2 CO2 molecules are released in two separate steps:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst CO2 is released when isocitrate is converted to \u03b1-ketoglutarate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESecond CO2 is released when \u03b1-ketoglutarate is converted to succinyl-CoA\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3 NADH molecules are produced in three steps:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst NADH from isocitrate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESecond NADH from \u03b1-ketoglutarate to succinyl-CoA\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThird NADH from malate to oxaloacetate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1 FADH2 is produced when succinate is converted to fumarate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1 GTP is produced during the conversion of succinyl-CoA to succinate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect because they either underestimate or overestimate the products. Remember that complete glucose oxidation requires two turns of the cycle since one glucose molecule produces two acetyl-CoA molecules through glycolysis and pyruvate dehydrogenase complex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["One turn of the citric acid cycle produces 2 CO2, 3 NADH, 1 FADH2, and 1 GTP from one acetyl-CoA molecule.","The citric acid cycle occurs in the mitochondrial matrix and requires oxygen as the final electron acceptor.","Complete glucose oxidation requires two turns of the cycle since one glucose molecule produces two acetyl-CoA molecules."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56542"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17512"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56542"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T20:31:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T20:32:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10202"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71071"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":